$y25  = Compute("0");


## Declare variables
Context()->variables->are(n=>'Real',r=>'Real',x=>'Real');

$P = Formula("$b/($a * x)")->reduce;
$Q = Formula("1/$a")->reduce;
$xP = Formula("x * $P")->reduce;
$xQ = Formula("x * x * $Q")->reduce;

$p  = Formula("$a*r*r+($b - $a)*r")->reduce;#x^{-1} term
$p1 = Formula("(r+1)*($a*r+$b)")->reduce;#constant term

$nm1  = Formula("n-1")->reduce;
$n   = Formula("n")->reduce;
$n1  = Formula("n+1")->reduce;
$n2  = Formula("n+2")->reduce;


$kn  = Formula("1")->reduce;
$kn2 = Formula("($a*n+$a*r+$b)*(n+r+1)")->reduce;
$r   = Formula("-$kn/$kn2")->reduce;



BEGIN_TEXT
$BBOLD (2) $EBOLD
Substituting \(y = x^r\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}c_k\ x^k\) into 
\($A x y'' +$B y'+ x y =0\), we get that
\{ BeginTable(center=>0).
      Row(['\(x^r\Bigg(\)',ans_rule(15),tablesubscript(width=>1),'\(x^{-1} + \)',ans_rule(15),tablesubscript(width=>1),'\( + \)',tablesum(sumvariable=>'\(n\)',lower=>'\(1\)',upper=>'\(\hskip 3pt\infty\)'),'\(\Big[\)',ans_rule(3),tablesubscript(),'\( + \)',ans_rule(20),tablesubscript(width=>4),'\(\Big]x^n\Bigg) = 0 \)'],separation=>1).
   EndTable();
\}


$BBOLD
The subscripts on the \(c\)'s should be increasing and numbers or in terms of \(n\).
$EBOLD
$PAR

$BBOLD (3) $EBOLD In this step, we will use the equation above to find the indicial roots and the recurrence relation of the differential equation.  
$PAR
$BBOLD (a) $EBOLD From the equation above, we know that the indicial roots of the differential equation are 
\(r=\)\{ ans_rule(10) \} and \(r=\)\{ ans_rule(10) \}.
$PAR
$BBOLD (b) $EBOLD From the constant term in the series above, we know that
$BCENTER
\{ BeginTable(center=>0).
      Row([tablesubscript(width=>1),'\( = \)',ans_rule(1)],separation=>1).
   EndTable();
\}
$ECENTER
$PAR
$BBOLD (c) $EBOLD From the series above, we find that the recurrence relation is 
$BCENTER
\{ BeginTable(center=>0).
      Row([tablesubscript(width=>3),'\( = \)',ans_rule(25),tablesubscript()," for ",ans_rule(2),'\( \geq \)',ans_rule(2)],separation=>1).
   EndTable();
\}
$ECENTER
$PAR

$BBOLD (4) $EBOLD The general solution to 
\($A x y'' +$B y'+ x y =0\)
is 
$BCENTER
\{ BeginTable(center=>0).
      Row(['\(y\)','\(=A\)',tablesuperscript(variable=>'\(x\)'),'\(\Bigg(\)',ans_rule(1),'\( + \)',ans_rule(2),'\(x + \)',ans_rule(7),'\(x^2 + \)',ans_rule(1),'\(x^3 + \)',ans_rule(7),'\(x^4 + \)',ans_rule(1),'\(x^5 + \cdots \Bigg) \)'],separation=>1).
      Row(['','\( + B\)',tablesuperscript(variable=>'\(x\)'),'\(\Bigg(\)',ans_rule(1),'\( + \)',ans_rule(2),'\(x + \)',ans_rule(7),'\(x^2 + \)',ans_rule(1),'\(x^3 + \)',ans_rule(7),'\(x^4 + \)',ans_rule(1),'\(x^5 + \cdots \Bigg) \)'],separation=>1).
   EndTable();
\}
$ECENTER
and
converges on the interval \{ ans_rule(10) \}.
